                				        <div id="content">
                    <div id="content-content" class="clear-block"> <script type="text/javascript">var re="";</script>
<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>07. "Fresh Air For the Lungs Induces Perfect Health." The Pullman Automatic Ventilator Company; York, PA; c.1904.</strong><br />       <p>As was the case in Europe, the Industrial Revolution sparked a tremendous urban migration in the United States as rural populations and new immigrants flocked to under-resourced cities lacking in adequate infrastructure. From 1840 to 1920, the urban U.S population grew from approximately 1.8 million to more than 54 million.<sup><a href="3511#fn7" id="ref7">7</a></sup>  Crowded in tenement housing without running water, ventilation or waste facilities, inhabitants unwittingly passed disease among each other, eventually culminating in a rash of deadly epidemics. As if the epidemiological factors weren&rsquo;t catastrophic enough, a new &ldquo;throwaway culture&rdquo; was also arising, in which &ldquo;the growth of markets for new products came to depend in part on the continuous disposal of old things,&rdquo;<sup><a href="3511#fn8" id="ref8">8</a></sup> further contributing to the magnitude of the waste problem.</p>

<p>Many factors contributed to the organized improvement of urban sanitation—the &ldquo;Great Sanitary Awakening.&rdquo; Chief among them was a growing awareness of the importance of sanitation and ventilation, even when predicated on theories now known to be erroneous (e.g. &ldquo;anti-contagionism&rdquo;). In the wake of this new awareness grew an entire industry, though by the 1930s businesses were clearly concerned as much about their bottom line as they were disease-prevention. Touting the &ldquo;earning power of the Nodis equipped lavatory,&rdquo; this brochure promises to convert expenses (i.e., &ldquo;red&rdquo;) &ldquo;into ACTUAL PROFITS&rdquo; so that &ldquo;the crusade against communicable diseases [can be] carried onward.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Interestingly, the patent holder for the Pullman Automatic Ventilator Company of York, PA—Charles Lewis Pullman—was the younger brother of George M. Pullman, engineer and founder of the Pullman Palace Car Company. Pullman was also the founder of the Pullman company town (since annexed by the City of Chicago), designed and built by Solon S. Beman between 1880 and 1885. Built according to the newfound wisdom of the time, no dwelling was designed more than two rooms deep in order to ensure access to both cross ventilation and sunlight.</p>
<br />
<sup id="fn7">7. Richard A. Pizzi, &ldquo;Apostles of cleanliness.&rdquo; <em>Modern Drug Discovery</em>, vol.5, no.5 (2002): 51.  <a href="3511#ref7" title="Jump back to footnote 7 in the text.">↩</a></sup> 

 <p><sup id="fn8">8. Kim Knowlton, &ldquo;Urban History, Urban Health.&rdquo; <em>Am J Public Health</em>, vol.91, no.12 (2001): 1944.<a href="3511#ref8" title="Jump back to footnote 8 in the text.">↩</a></sup></p><br /><br />
    	 "Tools of the Trade: 19th- and 20th-Century Architectural Trade Catalogs," Case 3, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, August 4, 2015-October 12, 2015.<br />
<br />
<a href="https://digital-libraries.artic.edu/cdm/ref/collection/mqc/id/68810">Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record</a><br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
